@flexiarg p4ng/agent-as-mana-unit-was-the-wrong-unit
@title Agent-as-Mana-Unit Was the Wrong Unit (precursor note)
@sigils [📜/誤]
@keywords mana, agent, session, unit, precursor, p4ng, attribution
@audience pattern theorists, anyone reading the mana-allostasis frame and wondering where the unit came from
@tone analytic-historical
@factor Discernment (vipassanā) — naming a flawed precursor explicitly so it can be inherited usefully
@style precursor-note
@references [structure/mana-allostasis structure/block-as-futonic-revolution invariant-coherence/drain-channel-shape p4ng/p4ng-agents]

! conclusion: 
  Earlier framings — p4ng-era multi-agent simulation, conceptual
  sketches around mana-as-budget — treated AGENTS as the natural
  unit of mana accounting. This was wrong, in a way that became
  visible only after the substrate framing landed. Mana attaches to
  SESSIONS, not agents. The agent-as-unit reading is preserved here
  as a flawed precursor — useful to read, useful to point to, not
  useful to act from.

  + context:
    p4ng-era pattern work modelled futon agents as semi-autonomous
    actors whose budget/license could meaningfully be tracked
    per-actor. The framing made sense in a multi-agent simulation
    context where each agent ran its own loop. It did not survive
    contact with operational reality, where:
      - One operator's session typically routes through multiple
        agents (Claude REPL, Codex, Tickle, Forum bots) in tight
        sequence, each contributing partial work to one coherent
        chunk.
      - The *felt cost* of allostatic load is borne by the operator,
        not by any individual agent. An agent has no metabolism
        beyond its turn.
      - Block-closure (the source of mana awards per
        `structure/mana-allostasis`) is an operator-attestable act,
        not an agent action.

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.
    + DIAGNOSTIC:
      Whenever discussing budget/license/mana around agents, check the
      unit. If "agent X is over budget" is the claim, ask: what would
      the analogous claim about the *session* containing agent X
      look like? If it loses meaning, the agent-unit framing has
      snuck in. Restore the session-unit framing.

    + REFERENCES:
      - structure/mana-allostasis — formalises the balance equation with sessions as the temporal frame.
      - structure/block-as-futonic-revolution — defines block-closure as operator-attestable.
      - invariant-coherence/drain-channel-shape — drain channels under the mana-allostasis faculty; sibling pluri-channel framing.
      - p4ng/p4ng-agents — the precursor multi-agent framing this note corrects.
      - M-bounded-in-flight-state V-6 — the verification thread that surfaced the unit error and named it.

    + WHAT-CARRIES-FORWARD:
      The precursor was right about the *shape* of the problem (some
      notion of budget/credit/dana is needed; pure unbounded action
      selection is wrong). It was wrong about the *unit*. The fix is
      to keep the budget concept and reattach it to sessions:
        - `nonstarter_mana.clj`'s `--session` parameter is the
          operational evidence that the corrected unit is already in
          production code.
        - `structure/mana-allostasis` formalises balance per session.
        - The candidate invariant `budgeted-action-selection/mana-gated-work`
          (futon5a queue run-064) is the family-level expression of
          the same shape with the corrected unit.

    + WHAT-WENT-WRONG:
      The precursor framing made three structural assumptions that
      looked plausible and turned out not to hold:
        1. *Agent autonomy* — that agents have enough independent
           continuity to bear a budget across turns. They don't; an
           agent's continuity lives in the session that hosts it.
        2. *Unit-of-attestation* — that agents can attest their own
           work-completion. They can't, in any way that survives the
           operator's distinct sense of "this is done." Block-closure
           requires operator attestation (see
           `structure/block-as-futonic-revolution`).
        3. *Per-agent metabolic state* — that "this agent is tired"
           is meaningful. It isn't. The operator is the one who tires;
           agents are stateless across calls.
